\fs40 Relational event model
\fs32 \
	A relational event is the interaction of a sender and receiver. In our case, the sender is a species and the receiver a region. A relational event\
	is generally defined a tripled of a sender, receiver and time of event. In our study the relational event is given by alien species, region and time of invasion\
	\
	The REM framework is capable of studying temporal patterns and it\'92s an adaptable hypothesis testing tool. \
	However due to the large number of possible local configurations (such as k-stars) it\'92s hard for a REM to keep track of the past configurations when applied to dynamics networks.\
\
	We define the Risk set as the set of all dyads for which, at a given time t, an event might occur.\
	We assume the waiting time T for an invasion to happen between a species and a region to be exponentially distributed. \
	The hazard function is the expected number of relational events in a time interval of lenght 1, conditionally on the previous network events \
\
	We model every invasion as a multivariate Poisson counting N. For a timestep t, the poisson counting N gives the number of invasions happened between r and s up to t.\
	A species is not allowed to leave a country and invade it afterward. Therefore, the counting process is bounded by 1.\
\

\fs40 LATENT SPACE\

\fs32 	We now dispose the species and regions into a latent space of dimension n. \
	The equation shows the latent space dynamcis. X is the latent state and Y is the observed state. \
\
	In our study, the observed state is the number of invasions, modelled as Poisson. The observed state is a result of the dynamics in the latent state and interaction in the REM.\
	The stochastic intensity of the counting process N is modelled by hazard lambda. Heuristically, we assume that lambda is a function of the distance of the nodes in the latent space.\
	The rates lambda are censured by multiplying by the matrix I. The matrix I entires are either one or zero depeding if an invasion of a species into a region has already occurred.\
\
	Inside the latent space, the position of the nodes in the latent space is constrained by the distance to all  nodes in the latent space. \
	The distances of the nodes in the latent space are given by their affinity to create a connection (which in our case is to invade) to a region. \
	We therefore expect species that have the tendency to co-invade to be close in the latent space and regions that are invaded by the same group of species to be close as well under 	the same argument. \
	Note that the position of the regions in the latent space has no direct relation with the real geospatial position in the world.\
	We are interested in studying the structure of the latent space X\
\
Our goal is to maximise the marginal likelihood, however a direct maximization is not possible. To infer on the strucutre of the latent space X and the parameters theta, sigma we use the EM algorithm. \
\
Our latent space formulation allows us to solve the computationally expensive expectation step using a Kalman Filter. We approximate the quantity Q in terms of its first two moments.\
\
However, the process y is not linear. Here I report the latent space equations in a more general way. The function f is the identity function in our case and h is a function dependent on the latent space. The function h is not linear because it\'92s Poisson Distributed but we can linearise it around the mean and reconduct to the basic linear problem by means of a taylor expansion. \
\
We now have all the ingredients to make inference about our latent space relational event model\
